<span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ mylinux ~] # cpio-icduv &lt;/ opt / etc.cpio</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># Note, cpio recovery path, if the package cpio backup is used when the absolute path, then the recovery time will be automatically restored to the absolute path, in this case all of the backup file will be restored to the / etc directory corresponding directory. Similarly, if the package is a relative path for backup, restore when they will return to relative path.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Through the above example, you can see, cpio can not directly read the file, it needs to each file or directory to know the full path name</span></span>Do not read the output of the find command just done this, so, cpio command with the use of general and find commands. In fact, the above example we have seen their combined usage. </div> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>','Function: cpio command is the way by redirecting the package file backup, restore, recovery tool, which can extract to \". Cpio\" or \". Tar\" at the end of the file.Using the format: cpio [Options]> the file name or device namecpio [options] <file name or device nameOption Description: Detailed...'),(62,'Linux','linux','en','/a/os/linux/2010/0727/368.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Linux system management and maintenance of the-dd command','Linux_system_management_and_maintenance_of_thedd_command','2010-07-27','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Features: Convert or copy files, and can back up the device.</span></span> </p><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Using the format: dd if = &quot;input_file&quot; of = &quot;output_file&quot; bs = &quot;block_size&quot; count = &quot;number&quot;</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">Option Description:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">if: is the input file, which can be equipment such as a disk partition or the entire disk.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">of: is the output file, it can be output devices such as disk, tape, and so on.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">bs: Specify a block size, if not specified, the default is 512 bytes.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">count: is &quot;bs&quot; number.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">For example:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">1. To / etc / inittab files to / opt / inittab.bak, use the following command:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ mylinux ~] # dd if = / etc / inittab of = / opt / inittab.bak</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">3 +1 records in</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">3 +1 records out</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ mylinux ~] # ls-al / etc / inittab / opt / inittab.bak</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-Rw-r - r - 1 root root 1666 Jul 22 17:37 / etc / inittab</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">-Rw-r - r - 1 root root 1666 Jul 23 08:09 / opt / inittab.bak</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># Note the above two documents, the size of any differences, are 1666 bytes, because there is no designated &quot;bs&quot; size, so the default is 512 bytes for a flat block, just above the &quot;3 +1&quot;, namely: 3 said There are 3 full 512 bytes of the block, and &quot;1&quot; means less than 512 bytes of that block.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">2. The / dev/sda2 partition backup the whole, save the backup file to the / opt directory, use the following command:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ mylinux ~] # dd if = / dev/sda2 of = / opt/sda2.back</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># This is the disk backup all the data in a partition, dd command can also back up the entire disk of the data, where the backup output path must not be &quot;/ dev/sda2&quot; where the partition, otherwise how are the backup endless.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">3. The above example, the backup package / opt/sda2.back back to the appropriate partition, use the following command:</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\">[Root @ mylinux ~] # dd if = / opt/sda2.back of = / dev/sda2</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># Special attention to the resumption of the target partition, we must first uninstall the target partition, until recovery is complete, mount.</span></span> </div><div> <span style=\"font-family: Arial\"><span style=\"font-size: small\"># Also need to note that the best backup and recovery partition the same partition, for example, in this case &quot;/ opt/sda6.back&quot; file is &quot;/ dev/sda2&quot; partition backup, then the recovery time is best to &quot;/ opt/sda6.back&quot; file back to &quot;/ dev/sda2&quot; partitions, or back to the size and &quot;/ dev/sda2&quot; under the same partition. Because the recovery of the target partition backup if the partition is larger than would be a waste of space; In contrast, less than the target partition backup recovery partition, the recovery time will be prompted to space.</span></span> </div> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>','Features: Convert or copy files, and can back up the device.Using the format: dd if = \"input_file\" of = \"output_file\" bs = \"block_size\" count = \"number\"Option Description:if: is the input file, which can be equipment such as a disk partition or the entire disk.of: is the output file, it can be...'),(63,'Linux','linux','en','/a/os/linux/2010/0725/362.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Linux system management and maintenance-tar command','Linux_system_management_and_maintenancetar_command','2010-07-25','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<table width=\"100%\"><tr><td><p> <b>tar command</b> </p><div> <b>1. Function</b> </div><div> tar is a <u><a href=\"http://www.ixdba.net/a/os/linux/\">Linux</a></u> file under the frequently used tool is packaged archive file or directory, go into a file, but not be compressed. The format is as follows: </div><div> tar [main options + secondary options] files or directories </div><div> tar command options are many, Here are some frequently used main options, such as shown in Table 4.31. </div><div> Table 4.31 tar command options and their description of the main </div><p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"97%\"><tbody><tr><td width=\"30%\"><div> Main options </div></td><td width=\"69%\"><div> Meaning </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"30%\"><div> -C </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"69%\"><div> Create a new file </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"30%\"><div> -R </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"69%\"><div> The archive file to be appended to the end of archive </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"30%\"><div> -T </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"69%\"><div> List archive files have been archived list </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"30%\"><div> -X </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"69%\"><div> From the packaged archive file to restore the </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"30%\"><div> -U </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"69%\"><div> Update archive files, with the new file to replace the original files in the file </div></td></tr></tbody></table></p><div></div><div> For more information on accessibility options shown in Table 4.32. </div><div> Table 4.32 tar command options and their description of the auxiliary </div><p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"97%\"><tbody><tr><td width=\"30%\"><div> Accessibility </div></td><td width=\"69%\"><div> Meaning </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"30%\"><div> -Z </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"69%\"><div> Gzip command in the document called the process of packing for compression / decompression file </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"30%\"><div> -W </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"69%\"><div> Restore the file, the file modification time all the time now set </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"30%\"><div> -J </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"69%\"><div> Bzip2 command in the document called the process of packing for compression / decompression file </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"30%\"><div> -Z </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"69%\"><div> Call compress command filter files </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"30%\"><div> -F </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"69%\"><div> &quot;-F&quot; option followed by the archive storage device, the default is the disk, you need to specify the file file name; if the tape, simply specify the tape device name. Note that in the &quot;-f&quot; option can not talk to any other option after that is &quot;-f&quot; tar command must be last option </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"30%\"><div> -V </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"69%\"><div> The process of creating the archive file specified, displays the name of each archive </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"30%\"><div> -P </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"69%\"><div> In the process of filing and maintaining the properties of the file does not change </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"30%\"><div> -N &quot;yyyy / mm / dd&quot; </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"69%\"><div> File after the specified date will be packaged into archive </div></td></tr><tr><td valign=\"top\" width=\"30%\"><div> - Exclude file </div></td><td valign=\"top\" width=\"69%\"><div> In the packaging process, not to specify the file file package </div></td></tr></tbody></table></p><div></div><div> <b>2. Example</b> </div><div> (1) / etc directory of the package all the files and show the detailed package files, settings package file named etc.tar, while saving the file to the / opt directory. </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup oracle] # tar-cvf / opt / etc.tar / etc </div><div> Here\'s the file name &quot;etc.tar&quot; is the name of our own taken lightly, Linux using tar command on the package out of the archives we generally use. Tar as the logo. </div><div> (2) the / etc directory and compress all the files packaged, and then displays the detailed package files, settings package file named etc.tar.gz, while saving the file to the / opt directory. </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup oracle] # tar-zcvf / opt / etc.tar.gz / etc </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup oracle] # tar-jcvf / opt/etc.tar.bz2 / etc </div><div> &quot;Zcvf&quot; option that is called after the package gzip command to compress files on the file, where file name &quot;etc.tar.gz&quot; is what we casually taken, &quot;. Tar&quot; tar command that is packaged. &quot; gz &quot;command that calls the gzip compression. Similarly, &quot;jcvf&quot; option that is called after the package bzip2 compressed files on the file command, the file name identified in the &quot;. Bz2&quot; said the command was called bzip2 compression. </div><div> Here the name of the archive file is not hard and fast rules, the above naming convention used, it is easy to let us know the type of file and the corresponding way to relieve stress, because of different compression and decompression methods are different. At the same time, this rule is we all acquiesced to a rule. If you do not like this rule can be named according to their own archive files like. </div><div> (3) access to the top / opt / etc.tar.gz archive content. </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup oracle] # tar-ztvf / opt / etc.tar.gz </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup oracle] # tar-jtvf / opt / etc.tar.gz </div><div></div><p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\"><tbody><tr><td width=\"62\"><div> Note </div></td><td width=\"498\"><div> &quot;Etc.tar.gz&quot; may contain many files, a screen can not be completed, then you can use the more command, for example, tar-zxvf / opt / etc.tar.gz | more. </div></td></tr></tbody></table></p><div></div><div> (4) / opt / etc.tar.gz extract to / usr / local / src under. </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup oracle] # cd / usr / local / src </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup src] # tar-zxvf / opt / etc.tar.gz </div><div> Under normal circumstances, you can put / opt / etc.tar.gz solved in any place where we first switched to the / usr / local / src directory, and then unlock / opt / etc.tar.gz, so / usr / local / src / etc directory that we unlock the directory. </div><div> (5) / etc directory of the package all the files backed up to / opt directory, and save each file permissions. </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup oracle] # tar-zcvpf / opt / etc.tar.gz / etc </div><div> (6) in / opt directory, just unlock the / opt / etc.tar.gz compressed file in the / etc / inittab file. </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup oracle] # cd / opt </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup opt] # tar-zxvf / opt / etc.tar.gz etc / inittab </div><div> We can begin with a &quot;tar-ztvf&quot; View &quot;etc.tar.gz&quot; file contains the file, and then find the need to unlock the files by way of the above extract. Behind the need to extract out of the specified file must be a by &quot;tar-ztvf&quot; displayed the full path of the file. So that in the / opt directory, extract a etc directory, and etc directory of the file inittab is that we need. </div><div> (7) Package Backup / var / log directory 2008/7/21 subsequent documents. </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup oracle] # tar-N &quot;2008/7/21&quot;-zcvf log.tar.gz / var / log </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup oracle]# Pwd </div><div> / Opt / oracle </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup oracle] # ls </div><div> log.tar.gz </div><div> (8) package backup / home directory and the / etc directory, but does not backup / home directory under the ixdba. </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup oracle] # tar-exclude / home / ixdba-zcvf myfile.tar.gz / home / * / etc </div><div> (9) the / etc directory to directly extract the compressed package / opt directory, without generating the packaged archive. </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup oracle] # cd / opt </div><div> [Root @ dbbackup opt] # tar-zcvf - / etc | tar-zxvf - </div><div> In the above command, followed by the &quot;f&quot; back &quot;-&quot; is to create the archive file output to standard output, &quot;|&quot; pipe symbol in Linux, said the command final &quot;-&quot; indicates that the tar command by incoming pipe need to extract the archive file as a source of data. </div> (Editor: South African Ant) </td></tr></table>','tar command1. Function tar is a Linux file under the frequently used tool is packaged archive file or directory, go into a file, but not be compressed. The format is as follows:  tar [main options + secondary options] files or directories  tar command options are many, Here are some frequently used...'),(64,'Linux','linux','en','/a/os/linux/2010/0725/361.html','http://www.ixdba.net','Linux system management and maintenance -bzip2/bunzip2 comm